6
00:00:51,033 --> 00:00:54,025
I didn't. . . . Sir? Sir?

7
00:00:54,673 --> 00:00:58,143
It won't happen again, sir.
I didn't want. . . .

8
00:01:11,073 --> 00:01:12,825
I didn't. . . .

9
00:01:15,913 --> 00:01:17,392
Private Arthur James Gardner. . .

10
00:01:17,553 --> 00:01:20,465
. . .you've been found guilty
as charged for the crime of murder.

11
00:01:20,673 --> 00:01:23,062
Your case has been appealed
three times. . .

12
00:01:23,233 --> 00:01:24,712
. . .and reviewed three times.

13
00:01:24,913 --> 00:01:28,030
The verdict of each court-martial
has been the same:

14
00:01:28,193 --> 00:01:29,512
Guilty as charged.

15
00:01:30,553 --> 00:01:33,784
Do you have anything to say before
sentence is carried out?

16
00:01:34,673 --> 00:01:36,504
I didn't mean it.

17
00:01:38,433 --> 00:01:39,752
l-- I'm sorry.

18
00:01:44,113 --> 00:01:45,944
I didn't mean to.

19
00:01:47,433 --> 00:01:49,628
I'm sorry.

20
00:02:01,633 --> 00:02:03,430
Open it up.

21
00:02:05,553 --> 00:02:07,191
Enjoy the show, major?

22
00:02:36,033 --> 00:02:37,466
I want to see Major Armbruster.

23
00:02:37,633 --> 00:02:40,352
-Just down the corridor--
-Yeah, I know where it is. I know.

24
00:02:42,513 --> 00:02:44,390
John. Good to see you.

25
00:02:44,553 --> 00:02:47,670
Don't you give me that. We had
dinner last night together, remember?

26
00:02:49,913 --> 00:02:53,303
Be nice. Take it easy.

27
00:02:55,993 --> 00:02:59,872
This time it's serious, John.
You've gotta cooperate.

28
00:03:00,473 --> 00:03:01,826
Let's go.

29
00:03:09,793 --> 00:03:12,466
Colonel.
General is waiting, major.

30
00:03:19,953 --> 00:03:21,545
Major Reisman, sir.

31
00:03:29,033 --> 00:03:30,785
Sit down, gentlemen. Sit down.

32
00:03:30,993 --> 00:03:32,506
-Sit down, major.
-Thank you, sir.

33
00:03:39,633 --> 00:03:42,352
Well, major, what did you think
of the hanging?

34
00:03:43,553 --> 00:03:46,465
Looked very efficient.
Then again, I'm not an expert.

35
00:03:46,673 --> 00:03:50,427
I meant, how did you
personally feel about it?

36
00:03:50,633 --> 00:03:52,669
It wasn't the nicest way
to spend an evening.

37
00:03:53,073 --> 00:03:55,792
Well, it wasn't staged
for your entertainment, you know.

38
00:03:55,953 --> 00:03:57,784
I hope Private Gardner
was aware of that.

39
00:03:57,993 --> 00:03:59,506
-Private who?
-Private Gardner.

40
00:03:59,673 --> 00:04:02,028
He was the object of the exercise.

41
00:04:03,353 --> 00:04:06,186
There happens to have
been a reason, major.

42
00:04:06,793 --> 00:04:09,102
I've got your service record here, major.

43
00:04:10,393 --> 00:04:14,147
A lot of fireworks. A lot of transfers.

44
00:04:14,353 --> 00:04:17,982
One tough scrape after another,
very short on discipline.

45
00:04:19,033 --> 00:04:21,547
Very short on discipline.

46
00:04:23,633 --> 00:04:25,908
I hear you did a pretty good job in Italy.

47
00:04:26,473 --> 00:04:30,068
Then you loused it up by exceeding your
orders. And that's not the first time.

48
00:04:30,273 --> 00:04:33,583
-I didn't write those reports, sir.
-What is that supposed to mean?

49
00:04:33,753 --> 00:04:36,028
I don't necessarily agree
with what's in them.

50
00:04:36,233 --> 00:04:39,543
-Maybe you'd like to write your own?
-No, thank you, sir.

51
00:04:40,593 --> 00:04:44,188
I'm not very interested in embroidery,
only results.

52
00:04:46,793 --> 00:04:49,432
Now, you hold it right there.

53
00:04:49,633 --> 00:04:52,625
This war was not started
for your private gratification.

54
00:04:52,793 --> 00:04:54,704
And you can be damn sure
that this Army. . .

55
00:04:54,873 --> 00:04:57,467
. . .isn't being run for your
personal convenience, either.

56
00:05:01,233 --> 00:05:04,066
You've been waiting for a transfer
for over two months now.

57
00:05:04,273 --> 00:05:07,310
With a record like yours,
you could go on waiting forever.

58
00:05:07,473 --> 00:05:11,386
However, I get orders too.
And right now I've got some. . .

59
00:05:11,593 --> 00:05:14,665
. . .that sound as if they were made
for somebody just like you.

60
00:05:14,833 --> 00:05:17,711
Personally, I don't go for this
behind-the-lines nonsense.

61
00:05:17,873 --> 00:05:21,707
As far as I'm concerned, a soldier's job
is to wear his uniform and kill the enemy.

62
00:05:22,713 --> 00:05:24,066
But that's another matter.

63
00:05:24,713 --> 00:05:27,102
I'm gonna ask General Denton
to read these orders. . .

64
00:05:27,273 --> 00:05:28,752
. . .just as they came down to us.

65
00:05:28,913 --> 00:05:31,222
After, if you have any questions, ask.
Understand?

66
00:05:31,393 --> 00:05:33,190
-Yes, sir.
-General.

67
00:05:36,673 --> 00:05:38,026
"Project Amnesty:

68
00:05:38,233 --> 00:05:40,588
You will select 12 prisoners
sentenced to death. . .

69
00:05:40,753 --> 00:05:44,666
. . .or long-term imprisonment for murder,
rape, robbery or other violent crimes.

70
00:05:44,833 --> 00:05:48,064
Train these prisoners in as much of the
behind-the-lines operations. . .

71
00:05:48,233 --> 00:05:50,906
. . .as they can absorb in a brief
but unspecified time.

72
00:05:51,113 --> 00:05:54,423
You'll then deliver them secretly
to Europe and prior to the invasion. . .

73
00:05:54,593 --> 00:05:58,666
. . .attack and destroy the target
specified: Overleaf. "

74
00:06:00,033 --> 00:06:01,625
-That's all?
-That's all.

75
00:06:02,913 --> 00:06:05,473
What about the target specified,
Overleaf?

76
00:06:05,673 --> 00:06:07,391
Doesn't concern you now.

77
00:06:07,793 --> 00:06:09,465
Well, what do you say, major?

78
00:06:09,753 --> 00:06:12,711
I'd say it confirms a suspicion
I've had for some time now, sir.

79
00:06:12,873 --> 00:06:15,148
Do you think we might share
that suspicion, major?

80
00:06:15,353 --> 00:06:16,388
I think you should.

81
00:06:16,593 --> 00:06:19,312
Since I'll have to assume we're
over here to win the war. . .

82
00:06:19,473 --> 00:06:21,065
. . .it wouldn't pay to advertise. . .

83
00:06:21,233 --> 00:06:23,952
. . .that one man we're working for
is a raving lunatic.

84
00:06:24,153 --> 00:06:27,623
Now, that's enough, major. You're here
to be briefed on an operation.

85
00:06:27,793 --> 00:06:30,432
You have permission to ask questions
about that operation.

86
00:06:30,593 --> 00:06:33,107
You do not have permission
to make personal comments. . .

87
00:06:33,313 --> 00:06:35,952
. . .concerning the officers
responsible for its conception.

88
00:06:36,113 --> 00:06:37,546
-Now, is that clear?
-Yes, sir.

89
00:06:37,713 --> 00:06:39,510
Ask relevant questions or shut up.

90
00:06:39,713 --> 00:06:42,352
Is it relevant to ask why I'm being
offered this mission?

91
00:06:42,513 --> 00:06:46,108
It's not, as you say, being offered.

92
00:06:46,793 --> 00:06:48,545
I'm volunteering.

93
00:06:48,713 --> 00:06:50,066
Exactly, major.

94
00:06:50,273 --> 00:06:52,707
I'm glad you look at these things
so realistically.

95
00:06:53,273 --> 00:06:56,948
I don't mean to appear unduly cautious,
but if my personal survival. . .

96
00:06:57,153 --> 00:06:59,428
. . .depends on the performance
of 12 deadheads. . .

97
00:06:59,593 --> 00:07:02,630
. . .it might be helpful to know exactly
what I'm training them for.

98
00:07:02,833 --> 00:07:05,472
Now, that's a very good question, major.

99
00:07:05,673 --> 00:07:08,904
-Armbruster, let's have the basic outline.
-Yes, sir.

100
00:07:11,153 --> 00:07:14,429
"The Germans are using a large chateau
near Rennes in Brittany. . .

101
00:07:14,633 --> 00:07:18,308
. . .as a rest center and a conference
place for general staff officers. "

102
00:07:18,513 --> 00:07:20,663
The target has no real
military value itself. . .

103
00:07:20,873 --> 00:07:24,343
. . .but with these conferences, discussion
groups and the like going on. . .

104
00:07:24,513 --> 00:07:27,630
. . .there's hardly a day when
there aren't a considerable number. . .

105
00:07:27,793 --> 00:07:30,023
. . .of important general officers
in residence.

106
00:07:30,193 --> 00:07:33,185
Usually with the benefit
of female companionship.

107
00:07:33,913 --> 00:07:37,269
"Eliminating a number of senior
officers couldn't but have the effect. . .

108
00:07:37,433 --> 00:07:39,264
. . .of disrupting
their chain of command. "

109
00:07:39,553 --> 00:07:42,192
The idea is simply that our men
are dropped by parachute.

110
00:07:42,353 --> 00:07:45,550
They enter the chateau and kill
as many senior officers as is possible. . .

111
00:07:45,713 --> 00:07:47,465
. . .in the time available.

112
00:07:48,793 --> 00:07:52,149
Naturally, the place is fortified
and heavily guarded.

113
00:07:52,353 --> 00:07:54,867
Naturally.
What's the deal with the men?

114
00:07:55,073 --> 00:07:57,985
None whatsoever. Let's have
no misunderstanding about that.

115
00:07:58,153 --> 00:07:59,950
It's exactly what it says, an amnesty.

116
00:08:00,113 --> 00:08:03,264
A temporary postponement.
You take it or leave it on that basis.

117
00:08:03,473 --> 00:08:06,624
Like you say, sir, let's not
have any misunderstandings.

118
00:08:06,833 --> 00:08:08,585
I don't like it. I think it stinks.

119
00:08:08,753 --> 00:08:10,345
I've had enough of your insolence.

120
00:08:10,513 --> 00:08:12,902
It's not a question of insolence
but of practicality.

121
00:08:13,113 --> 00:08:15,422
I'm the guy that's being asked
to sell this idea. . .

122
00:08:15,593 --> 00:08:17,663
. . .to 12 happy, smiling faces, right?

123
00:08:18,473 --> 00:08:21,704
They do have an alternative way to go,
you know.

124
00:08:22,513 --> 00:08:25,983
-That's no way for anybody to go.
-Oh, the hell you say, major.

125
00:08:26,153 --> 00:08:28,872
Why, I know a lot of people
who should go exactly that way.

126
00:08:32,873 --> 00:08:34,226
But that's beside the point.

127
00:08:34,393 --> 00:08:37,226
Now, come on, major,
what's your basic objection?

128
00:08:37,433 --> 00:08:40,903
These men are, by definition,
incapable of any discipline or authority. . .

129
00:08:41,073 --> 00:08:42,552
. . .much less intensive training.

130
00:08:42,713 --> 00:08:45,705
If there isn't a possibility
for a remission of their sentence. . .

131
00:08:45,873 --> 00:08:49,582
. . .they have nothing to look forward to
and no reason to cooperate, right?

132
00:08:50,993 --> 00:08:54,827
Got a point.
You got a point, major.

133
00:08:55,753 --> 00:08:57,869
However, as you know,
I don't have the power. . .

134
00:08:58,033 --> 00:09:00,263
. . .to reverse the findings
of a court-martial.

135
00:09:00,473 --> 00:09:03,306
You do have the power to commute
the sentence of such a court.

136
00:09:03,473 --> 00:09:04,872
-Excuse me, general.
-Yes?

137
00:09:05,073 --> 00:09:08,952
You do have authority under the Visiting
Forces Act to make such a ruling.

138
00:09:09,153 --> 00:09:11,872
-Visiting Forces Act?
-Yes, sir.

139
00:09:15,113 --> 00:09:16,751
All right, major, you got a deal.

140
00:09:17,553 --> 00:09:20,386
Let's say that if any of these men
distinguish themselves. . .

141
00:09:20,593 --> 00:09:24,381
. . .then we will give serious consideration
to commuting their sentences.

142
00:09:24,593 --> 00:09:26,265
That's no deal.

143
00:09:26,913 --> 00:09:29,905
Who's to say whether they really
distinguish themselves or not?

144
00:09:30,113 --> 00:09:32,263
You can leave that decision to me.

145
00:09:32,433 --> 00:09:36,108
But remember, the other alternative
will apply with equal force.

146
00:09:36,313 --> 00:09:39,066
Any breach of security,
any failure of discipline. . .

147
00:09:39,233 --> 00:09:41,667
. . .those prisoners go right back
where they came from.

148
00:09:41,873 --> 00:09:43,386
-Understood?
-Yes, sir.

149
00:09:43,593 --> 00:09:45,231
Good. Anything more, gentlemen?

150
00:09:45,753 --> 00:09:48,665
Well, yes, sir. I noticed
Colonel Breed in the waiting room.

151
00:09:48,873 --> 00:09:51,467
I wondered whether he was
connected with this operation.

152
00:09:52,273 --> 00:09:55,902
-What if he is?
-I'd be very unhappy, sir.

153
00:09:58,313 --> 00:10:01,589
Major, Colonel Breed
is your superior officer.

154
00:10:01,793 --> 00:10:04,261
And you will behave
accordingly, at all times.

155
00:10:04,473 --> 00:10:06,828
-Is that clear?
-Yes, sir.

156
00:10:08,753 --> 00:10:12,587
Now, it so happens that Colonel Breed
is not concerned with this operation.

157
00:10:12,753 --> 00:10:16,189
But he is running the parachute school
where part of your training will be.

158
00:10:16,393 --> 00:10:19,942
I don't want to hear any complaints,
from either of you.

159
00:10:21,193 --> 00:10:24,265
Now, you've got a job to do,
mister, so move it.

160
00:10:24,753 --> 00:10:25,822
Yes, sir.

161
00:10:27,433 --> 00:10:28,422
Thank you, gentlemen.

162
00:10:37,073 --> 00:10:39,826
Major Reisman seems to be heading
to his own court-martial.

163
00:10:39,993 --> 00:10:42,427
He's the most ill-mannered,
ill-disciplined officer. . .

164
00:10:42,593 --> 00:10:44,504
. . .it's ever been my displeasure to meet.

165
00:10:44,713 --> 00:10:46,305
You think so, Denton?

166
00:10:46,513 --> 00:10:51,189
You may be right.
But he's sure right about one thing.

167
00:10:51,393 --> 00:10:54,510
Somebody up there must be
a raving lunatic.

168
00:10:55,513 --> 00:10:57,071
Let's get Colonel Breed in here.

169
00:11:09,633 --> 00:11:10,622
Open.

170
00:11:10,793 --> 00:11:14,183
All right, you men,
this is an exercise period.

171
00:11:14,393 --> 00:11:15,906
So exercise!

172
00:11:31,473 --> 00:11:33,862
Major Reisman, Sergeant Bowren, sir.

173
00:11:35,153 --> 00:11:38,145
-Have the prisoners fall in.
-Sir.

174
00:11:38,353 --> 00:11:43,029
Prisoners, fall in.
All right, come on now. Get with it!

175
00:11:45,793 --> 00:11:48,591
-Come on, come on.
-Move it!

176
00:11:48,753 --> 00:11:52,029
Come on, move!
Hey, you, move, I said, move.

