About face!

216
00:15:41,233 --> 00:15:43,542
Left, march!

217
00:15:46,473 --> 00:15:47,508
Squad, halt!

218
00:15:48,473 --> 00:15:52,102
Right face! At ease.

219
00:15:52,313 --> 00:15:55,510
Now, what did I say to you?
Or maybe you don't understand English!

220
00:15:56,833 --> 00:15:59,905
-What's the matter, Number 11 ?
-I got a pain.

221
00:16:03,713 --> 00:16:07,023
-Where does it hurt?
-Well, I'll tell you. It's. . . .

222
00:16:08,433 --> 00:16:10,708
I wish you would.
And do it correctly, please.

223
00:16:10,873 --> 00:16:14,229
Oh, I don't have to say, sir, I. . . .
To you or anyone else.

224
00:16:14,393 --> 00:16:17,590
And I don't have to march, either.
And I know the rules.

225
00:16:18,073 --> 00:16:19,506
Why don't you have to march?

226
00:16:19,673 --> 00:16:23,143
Because condemned men
don't have to drill.

227
00:16:26,233 --> 00:16:28,793
And there's nothing you can
do about it, mister.

228
00:16:29,633 --> 00:16:30,622
What's your name, son?

229
00:16:34,433 --> 00:16:35,661
Eleven.

230
00:16:37,153 --> 00:16:39,587
His name is Franko, sir.

231
00:16:40,953 --> 00:16:43,831
Franko, come over here a minute.
Come on.

232
00:16:57,913 --> 00:17:02,225
Look, you little bastard, either you
march or I'll beat your brains out.

233
00:17:02,393 --> 00:17:03,667
Understand?

234
00:17:18,513 --> 00:17:19,787
What'd you see, sergeant?

235
00:17:19,953 --> 00:17:23,389
I saw the major attacked by the prisoner
and forced to defend himself, sir.

236
00:17:23,753 --> 00:17:26,267
All right, have the prisoner
taken back to his cell.

237
00:17:26,473 --> 00:17:27,986
Take his head, I'll get his feet.

238
00:17:28,153 --> 00:17:30,792
Now let's see what they can do
with a little close-order.

239
00:17:30,953 --> 00:17:32,466
Yes, sir.

240
00:17:33,913 --> 00:17:36,507
Squad, ten-hut!

241
00:17:38,553 --> 00:17:39,986
Right face.

242
00:17:41,593 --> 00:17:44,471
Forward, march! Hut.

243
00:17:45,273 --> 00:17:47,389
Squad, halt!

244
00:17:48,233 --> 00:17:50,542
About face!

245
00:17:51,193 --> 00:17:53,582
Forward, march!

246
00:18:04,633 --> 00:18:07,272
General prisoner Franko, Victor, sir.

247
00:18:23,913 --> 00:18:25,266
So how's the jaw?

248
00:18:26,513 --> 00:18:29,869
If you're gonna act tough, you should
learn how to take care of yourself.

249
00:18:30,073 --> 00:18:31,506
You really should.

250
00:18:31,673 --> 00:18:33,743
You're worried about my jaw?

251
00:18:36,033 --> 00:18:38,228
Franko's pain bothers the major?

252
00:18:38,833 --> 00:18:41,666
You were a big man with
the syndicate back in Chicago?

253
00:18:43,913 --> 00:18:44,902
You've seen my record.

254
00:18:45,073 --> 00:18:47,985
Yeah, I've seen your record,
so let's knock it off, huh?

255
00:18:48,193 --> 00:18:50,423
So, what happens first
when you hit London?

256
00:18:50,593 --> 00:18:55,144
You get involved in a penny-ante stickup
and start blasting and kill some old guy.

257
00:18:55,313 --> 00:18:58,225
And come away with what?

258
00:18:58,673 --> 00:19:02,586
-What did you have when they got you?
-What did I have? What do you mean?

259
00:19:02,753 --> 00:19:05,062
Come on, big shot.
How much money did you have?

260
00:19:05,233 --> 00:19:07,224
I had enough.

261
00:19:08,353 --> 00:19:12,949
Two pounds and 10 shilling.
That's almost 10 dollars.

262
00:19:14,033 --> 00:19:16,501
You're gonna get yourself hung
for a lousy 10 bucks.

263
00:19:16,953 --> 00:19:19,342
-What's that to you?
-Nothing.

264
00:19:19,513 --> 00:19:22,471
Then why don't you get off my back?
You didn't come to visit me.

265
00:19:22,633 --> 00:19:23,622
What do you want?

266
00:19:23,793 --> 00:19:26,512
I don't care if they hang you
for 10 dollars or 10 cents.

267
00:19:26,673 --> 00:19:28,629
It makes no difference to me.

268
00:19:29,193 --> 00:19:33,869
But it just so happens that temporarily
I got a little pull around here.

269
00:19:34,073 --> 00:19:37,224
And I might be able to get you
off the hook, if I wanted to.

270
00:19:43,793 --> 00:19:45,306
Are you a general?

271
00:19:45,513 --> 00:19:49,062
You're not a general, and only
a general can grant my reprieve.

272
00:19:49,273 --> 00:19:50,865
Look, stupid.

273
00:19:52,953 --> 00:19:54,306
I'm making you a proposition.

274
00:19:54,473 --> 00:19:56,668
All I want from you
is a straight yes or no.

275
00:19:58,793 --> 00:20:01,671
-You talk, I'll listen.
-Okay.

276
00:20:02,473 --> 00:20:06,102
You either can sweat out the two days
you have before the hanging. . .

277
00:20:06,273 --> 00:20:08,582
. . .or you join an outfit
that I'm putting together.

278
00:20:08,793 --> 00:20:12,149
If you do that, I'll have you
out of here in less than 24 hours.

279
00:20:12,313 --> 00:20:15,623
But you'll be worked to death, and
there's not a beating you won't take.

280
00:20:18,833 --> 00:20:21,666
And then
when I'm satisfied with you. . .

281
00:20:21,833 --> 00:20:25,348
. . .you'll go where the Army tells you.
Chances are you'll get killed anyway.

282
00:20:25,513 --> 00:20:26,946
You don't know Victor Franko.

283
00:20:28,073 --> 00:20:29,711
-Guard.
-All right, what's the deal?

284
00:20:29,873 --> 00:20:31,511
What's the deal if I do stay alive?

285
00:20:31,713 --> 00:20:33,465
-Might get off the hook.
-Count me in.

286
00:20:33,673 --> 00:20:37,268
But you foul up once,
anywhere along the line, just once. . .

287
00:20:37,473 --> 00:20:39,828
. . .and you'll be back here
at the end of a rope.

288
00:20:40,033 --> 00:20:43,423
Hey. Hey, wait a minute. Wait a minute!
What's the matter with you?

289
00:20:43,633 --> 00:20:45,783
You think I want to die?

290
00:20:51,953 --> 00:20:54,183
If you do, then you don't
know Victor Franko.

291
00:20:54,953 --> 00:20:56,147
How come you speak German?

292
00:20:57,033 --> 00:20:59,183
Because my old man was
a coal miner in Silesia.

293
00:20:59,393 --> 00:21:02,590
If he didn't speak German,
he didn't dig coal and he didn't eat.

294
00:21:02,793 --> 00:21:05,466
That was the language he spoke
when he came to the States?

295
00:21:05,713 --> 00:21:07,385
Pretty tough job in those days.

296
00:21:07,593 --> 00:21:09,345
Yeah, it still is.

297
00:21:09,553 --> 00:21:13,626
I don't like officers,
not any of them, and I never have.

298
00:21:15,753 --> 00:21:17,630
But you were one yourself,
weren't you?

299
00:21:18,953 --> 00:21:20,909
Yeah, three lousy days.

300
00:21:21,673 --> 00:21:24,233
Somebody must have thought
you'd make a good officer.

301
00:21:24,633 --> 00:21:26,828
They made a big mistake, didn't they?

302
00:21:27,273 --> 00:21:29,787
Well, I thought you claimed
he was going over the hill.

303
00:21:29,993 --> 00:21:32,302
What the hell are you talking about,
"claimed"?

304
00:21:32,473 --> 00:21:34,429
He was going over the hill.

305
00:21:34,993 --> 00:21:37,951
My outfit was pinned down by
the worst crossfire you ever saw.

306
00:21:38,153 --> 00:21:41,509
Half of them bleeding to death.
And this lover took off like a rabbit. . .

307
00:21:41,673 --> 00:21:43,504
. . .with the medical supplies
on his back.

308
00:21:43,713 --> 00:21:45,943
The only way to stop him
was to shoot him.

309
00:21:47,593 --> 00:21:49,345
Anyhow, he had it coming.

310
00:21:50,073 --> 00:21:53,622
Yeah. But you only made
one mistake, huh?

311
00:21:55,833 --> 00:21:57,107
Guard.

312
00:21:59,553 --> 00:22:01,828
You let somebody see you do it.

313
00:22:10,953 --> 00:22:13,706
General prisoner Maggott, A.J., sir.

314
00:22:17,793 --> 00:22:20,466
"Maggott, A.J. Death by hanging. "

315
00:22:20,633 --> 00:22:21,622
Hey, midnight.

316
00:22:21,833 --> 00:22:25,382
Be a real good boy, now, and maybe
I'll let you eat with the white folks.

317
00:22:37,273 --> 00:22:40,026
Well, Maggott, I see you've got
a sense of humor.

318
00:22:41,433 --> 00:22:45,824
The all-American hero,
laughing in the face of death.

319
00:22:51,553 --> 00:22:54,147
They're not gonna hang me, major.

320
00:22:55,993 --> 00:22:58,746
I never raped that evil slut. . .

321
00:22:59,633 --> 00:23:02,705
. . .or any other creature.

322
00:23:02,873 --> 00:23:05,433
The Lord gave me that woman
and told me to chastise her.

323
00:23:05,633 --> 00:23:07,669
Then he told you to beat her
to death, huh?

324
00:23:07,873 --> 00:23:10,182
I only do what I'm called on to do.

325
00:23:12,073 --> 00:23:16,703
I was in a state of grace.
And that woman. . .

326
00:23:16,873 --> 00:23:18,545
. . .she tried to soil my spirit.

327
00:23:18,753 --> 00:23:20,630
Well, I'm sure you were, Maggott.

328
00:23:20,833 --> 00:23:24,064
But it seems to me I remember
a quotation that goes like:

329
00:23:24,273 --> 00:23:25,422
Vengeance is mine.

330
00:23:27,393 --> 00:23:31,784
Vengeance is mine.
I will repay, sayeth the Lord.

331
00:23:31,993 --> 00:23:34,666
Paul to the Romans, Chapter 12.

332
00:23:35,473 --> 00:23:37,862
Exactly. Now, isn't that
supposed to mean. . .

333
00:23:38,073 --> 00:23:40,906
. . .that we leave punishment
of the transgressors to his hands?

334
00:23:41,113 --> 00:23:45,072
That's right, major.
That's exactly what it means.

335
00:23:45,273 --> 00:23:49,391
But it doesn't restrict him to the kind
of tools he would use, now does it?

336
00:23:49,593 --> 00:23:53,472
And like I told you, major,
I only do what I'm called on to do.

337
00:23:54,193 --> 00:23:57,151
You know, Maggott, I don't think
you're going to hang after all.

338
00:23:59,633 --> 00:24:04,070
I think a man like you is destined
for higher things. Guard.

339
00:24:08,473 --> 00:24:13,467
Besides, us Southern boys have
to stick together now, don't we?

340
00:24:19,833 --> 00:24:22,028
I sure didn't mean to kill that fella.

341
00:24:22,233 --> 00:24:25,350
But you do like I say,
and maybe they won't hang you.

342
00:24:25,553 --> 00:24:28,431
Fixing to kill me some other way?

343
00:24:28,633 --> 00:24:30,112
It might not come to that.

344
00:24:30,993 --> 00:24:34,668
I reckon the folks would be a sight
happier if I died like a soldier.

345
00:24:37,793 --> 00:24:39,465
Can't say I would.

346
00:24:39,833 --> 00:24:42,347
Who does this hotshot major
think he is?

347
00:24:42,513 --> 00:24:44,583
Making us play wet nurses
to a bunch of scum.

348
00:24:44,753 --> 00:24:46,345
Corporal Morgan.

349
00:24:46,553 --> 00:24:50,432
If you can't find something to do,
I'll find something for you.

350
00:24:51,793 --> 00:24:53,511
Now, move it.

351
00:24:56,193 --> 00:24:59,105
Don't sweet-talk me, whitey.
You know why I'm here.

352
00:24:59,313 --> 00:25:02,032
Or maybe you think I should've let
those cracker bastards. . .

353
00:25:02,193 --> 00:25:03,785
. . .go right ahead and castrate me?

354
00:25:04,193 --> 00:25:06,309
Seeing what those guys
tried to do to you. . .

355
00:25:06,473 --> 00:25:10,625
. . .I'd say that you had
considerable justification.

356
00:25:11,673 --> 00:25:16,508
Thank you, Mr. Major, sir.
I really do thank you for that.

357
00:25:17,913 --> 00:25:22,065
But the court didn't agree, right?
So where does that leave you?

358
00:25:22,273 --> 00:25:25,390
I'm offering you an alternative,
which means you can keep fighting.

359
00:25:25,593 --> 00:25:28,187
-Who for, major?
-For yourself, if you want.

360
00:25:28,393 --> 00:25:31,385
But the Krauts,
they're the real master-race merchants.

361
00:25:31,593 --> 00:25:33,470
That's your war, man, not mine.

362
00:25:33,633 --> 00:25:36,511
You don't like the Krauts,
major, you fight them.

363
00:25:37,553 --> 00:25:39,703
Me, I'll pick my own enemies.

364
00:25:39,913 --> 00:25:43,667
That's your privilege. But you won't
be able to exercise it much longer.

365
00:25:43,833 --> 00:25:45,266
Guard.

366
00:25:45,433 --> 00:25:49,585
Because on March 25th,
you have a date with the hangman.

367
00:25:53,073 --> 00:25:55,462
That's just six days from now.

368
00:26:02,713 --> 00:26:04,669
Buenos das, major.

369
00:26:06,993 --> 00:26:10,190
You know, sergeant, going over
the transcript of that man's trial. . .

370
00:26:10,393 --> 00:26:12,429
. . .there are a couple of things
I don't get.

371
00:26:13,233 --> 00:26:16,031
Did he ever claim
that he didn't do it?

372
00:26:16,233 --> 00:26:19,908
I beg your pardon, but you haven't been
around prisons very much, have you?

373
00:26:20,113 --> 00:26:24,072
You see, the first thing one learns
in prison, everybody is innocent.

374
00:26:24,553 --> 00:26:27,829
This one, he doesn't say too much
about that one way or another.

375
00:26:28,033 --> 00:26:32,743
He's only disturbed because we don't
allow him to have strings for his guitar.

376
00:26:32,913 --> 00:26:34,744
Sergeant, did you ever lose a man. . .

377
00:26:34,913 --> 00:26:37,108
. . .because he hung himself
with a guitar string?

378
00:26:37,273 --> 00:26:39,662
No, sir, I haven't,
and I'm not about to.

379
00:26:39,873 --> 00:26:42,341
Well, if he makes the trip,
see he gets the strings.

380
00:26:42,513 --> 00:26:43,787
Yes, sir.

381
00:26:49,473 --> 00:26:50,986
Attention!

382
00:26:57,833 --> 00:27:01,223
-Tell the men to be seated.
-Yes, sir. Take seats!

383
00:27:02,833 --> 00:27:04,107
-Guards out.
-Sir, l--

384
00:27:04,313 --> 00:27:06,463
-Guards out.
-Yes, sir.

385
00:27:06,753 --> 00:27:09,187
You heard him. Guards, out!

386
00:27:19,953 --> 00:27:23,741
My name, for those of you
who may have forgotten, is Reisman.

387
00:27:24,593 --> 00:27:28,552
You've all volunteered for a mission
which gives you just three ways to go:

388
00:27:28,713 --> 00:27:32,626
You can foul up in training and be sent
back here for execution of sentence. . .

389
00:27:32,793 --> 00:27:34,385
. . .or you can foul up in combat. . .

390
00:27:34,593 --> 00:27:37,027
. . .in which case
I'll blow your brains out. . .

391
00:27:37,233 --> 00:27:40,942
. . .or you can do as you're told,
in which case you might just get by.

392
00:27:41,153 --> 00:27:42,950
You must not attempt to escape.

393
00:27:43,113 --> 00:27:45,388
There will be no excuses,
there will be no appeal.

394
00:27:45,913 --> 00:27:48,711
Any breach of either of these conditions
by any one of you. . .

395
00:27:48,873 --> 00:27:52,183
. . .means you'll all be shipped back
for immediate execution of sentence.

396
00:27:53,433 --> 00:27:55,708
You are therefore dependent
upon each other.

397
00:27:55,913 --> 00:27:58,473
Any one of you try anything smart. . .

398
00:27:58,673 --> 00:28:01,392
. . .and the 12 of you get it
right in the head, all right?

399
00:28:04,473 --> 00:28:06,464
So try to remember that.

400
00:28:07,433 --> 00:28:08,786
Now, are there any questions?

401
00:28:13,473 --> 00:28:14,747
Sir?

402
00:28:17,873 --> 00:28:19,989
Do we have to eat with niggers?

403
00:28:25,993 --> 00:28:28,143
It's all right.
The gentleman from the South. . .

404
00:28:28,353 --> 00:28:31,390
. . .made some kind of inquiries
about the dining arrangements.

405
00:28:31,553 --> 00:28:34,909
He and his colleagues are discussing
the place-card settings. All right?

406
00:28:35,113 --> 00:28:37,707
Yes, sir. Thank you, sir.

407
00:28:41,473 --> 00:28:44,271
Look, corporal, fellas,
let's get with it, right? Remember?

408
00:28:44,473 --> 00:28:47,112
Baseball, pitching?
Chicago's always had the pitching.

409
00:28:47,273 --> 00:28:49,343
But now, as far as--
As far as hitting goes. . .

410
00:28:49,553 --> 00:28:52,750
. . .well, my sister, she can hit
better than half them fellas.

411
00:28:54,033 --> 00:28:55,591
Let's move it out!

412
00:29:00,713 --> 00:29:04,262
-Well, what do you think, sergeant?
-I think you'll do just fine, sir.

413
00:29:04,473 --> 00:29:06,828
Don't give me that.
I said, what do you think?

414
00:29:09,993 --> 00:29:12,632
I think the first chance
one of them lovers gets. . .

415
00:29:12,833 --> 00:29:16,064
. . .he's gonna shoot the major
right in the head, sir.

416
00:29:17,673 --> 00:29:19,664
-Thank you, sergeant.
-Sir.

417
00:29:21,313 --> 00:29:23,543
Okay, Franko. Let's go.

418
00:29:26,873 --> 00:29:28,465
All right, move it out.

419
00:30:03,673 --> 00:30:04,708
Come on.

420
00:30:26,233 --> 00:30:27,222
Over there.

421
00:30:34,633 --> 00:30:37,545
Sergeant, have the men fall in,
facing me.

422
00:30:37,713 --> 00:30:41,626
Sir. All right, on your feet. Fall in
over here, double-quick! Come on now!

423
00:30:43,113 --> 00:30:45,149
Come on, snap it up.
Snap it up!

424
00:30:48,753 --> 00:30:51,062
Jiminez, get in there!

425
00:30:52,673 --> 00:30:54,391
Ten-hut!

426
00:30:55,673 --> 00:30:58,506
All right, Franko, get rid
of that cigarette.

427
00:31:00,553 --> 00:31:01,542
Thank you.

428
00:31:03,153 --> 00:31:05,542
This will be your new home
until further notice.

429
00:31:06,073 --> 00:31:09,065
What there is of it will be built
by you, but the construction. . .

430
00:31:09,233 --> 00:31:11,349
. . .will in no way interfere
with your training.

431
00:31:11,553 --> 00:31:15,262
So the sooner you get it up, the sooner
you'll be sleeping in out of the rain.

432
00:31:16,273 --> 00:31:17,945
-Sergeant.
-Sir?

433
00:31:18,353 --> 00:31:22,585
You're in charge. I want this compound
up and completed within the month.

434
00:31:23,153 --> 00:31:24,268
Thank you.

435
00:32:44,233 --> 00:32:46,872
If this place was on fire,
it'd burn to the ground.

436
00:32:47,073 --> 00:32:48,791
Come on, what are you doing?

437
00:32:48,993 --> 00:32:52,110
All right, come on. Let's move.
Come on.

438
00:32:56,273 --> 00:32:58,833
Hey, Maggott, what are you? German?

439
00:33:10,993 --> 00:33:13,302
Hey, what are you trying to do,
break the window?

440
00:33:13,513 --> 00:33:15,504
All right, sergeant, fall them in.

441
00:33:16,433 --> 00:33:18,788
Fall in, in front of the hut.
On the double!

442
00:33:18,953 --> 00:33:20,352
Round it up!

443
00:33:24,713 --> 00:33:25,907
At ease.

444
00:33:29,113 --> 00:33:31,308
All right, that'll be all for today.

445
00:33:31,633 --> 00:33:33,988
How come they got
all the comforts of home?

446
00:33:34,393 --> 00:33:37,988
Why can't we put our floor in?
Why can't we put our windows in?

447
00:33:38,193 --> 00:33:41,230
-Franko's right.
-I'd rather sleep in my cell.

448
00:33:41,793 --> 00:33:44,910
Mr. Franko, with his keen eye
for detail. . .

449
00:33:45,073 --> 00:33:48,190
. . .has noted that the prisoners'
quarters are not yet ready.

450
00:33:49,513 --> 00:33:51,629
The answer to that is simple:

451
00:33:51,833 --> 00:33:54,472
You are not yet ready
to occupy that hut. . .

452
00:33:55,073 --> 00:33:57,667
. . .with the degree of comfort
that you would like.

453
00:33:58,513 --> 00:34:01,789
When I think that you've earned
that privilege, I'll let you know.

454
00:34:03,513 --> 00:34:05,708
Reveille is at 0530.

455
00:34:05,913 --> 00:34:07,232
That is all. Sergeant.

456
00:34:07,713 --> 00:34:10,068
Sir. You heard the man, chow time!

457
00:34:10,273 --> 00:34:11,706
Dismissed!

458
00:34:14,033 --> 00:34:16,911
That's it, fellas. Speak up, boys.
Speak up.

459
00:34:22,393 --> 00:34:24,861
Wind it up, strike one!

460
00:34:25,833 --> 00:34:29,143
Hey, Joseph, is that the way
they did it in the Polish navy?

461
00:34:29,513 --> 00:34:31,310
You won't win any cigars that way.

462
00:34:37,033 --> 00:34:38,830
Hey, Franko, number please.

463
00:34:38,993 --> 00:34:40,790
Ask the operator for my nickel back.

464
00:34:40,993 --> 00:34:43,951
Why don't you guys
just dry up and blow away?

465
00:34:53,273 --> 00:34:55,946
Meanwhile, on the Atlantic wall...

466
00:34:56,153 --> 00:34:58,986
... the German forces
have been preparing...

467
00:34:59,193 --> 00:35:01,753
...a few nice surprises for you,
gentlemen...

468
00:35:01,953 --> 00:35:03,671
...just in case Mr. Churchill...

469
00:35:03,833 --> 00:35:07,872
...is really foolish enough
to attempt an invasion.

470
00:35:08,513 --> 00:35:11,471
He may not be
unduly worried about this...

471
00:35:11,633 --> 00:35:15,546
...but then, of course, he will not
be taking any active part...

472
